# Contributing to Codename Domodossola

Thank you for contributing to Codename Domodossola.

This repository is a governed specification and implementation workspace. Contributions are welcome, but official identifiers and catalog entries are not self-assigned.

## 1. Scope of contributions

Contributions may include:
- documentation improvements
- new or revised `TECH_ID` proposals
- new or revised `NODE_IMP` proposals
- firmware implementations
- hardware implementations
- tests, validation material, and build tooling
- bug fixes and clarifications

Contributions should preserve the existing architecture, naming discipline, and catalog governance model.

## 2. Repository model

Codename Domodossola uses a single repository with multiple content classes, each governed by its own license and directory rules.

The repository contains:
- documentation and normative text
- catalog entries and their descriptive material
- firmware and software artifacts
- hardware and manufacturing artifacts
- tooling and validation material

The canonical meaning of `TECH_ID` and `NODE_IMP` is defined in the documentation layer, not in implementation files.

## 3. Official identifiers and namespace governance

Official `TECH_ID` and `NODE_IMP` values are allocated only by the project maintainer.

The official namespace is tied to the project’s `MAGIC` value. A fork that establishes independent governance MUST use a different `MAGIC`.

Contributors MUST NOT:
- allocate official identifiers for themselves
- introduce vendor-private identifier ranges
- reserve unofficial namespace blocks for future use
- represent temporary local identifiers as official catalog items

## 4. Proposed items and temporary identifiers

During design and implementation work, contributors may create **Proposed** items to allow a bundle of technologies and node implementations to interact before formal review.

A Proposed item is:
- development-stage
- not yet admitted to the official catalog
- subject to change
- intended for local testing and review

A Proposed item MAY be accompanied by proposed modifications to the normative documents, which MUST be explicitly identified and declared as a dependency of the submission. Such item MAY operate under its declared proposed spec modifications; this is not a violation provided the dependency is explicitly declared.

Temporary identifiers for Proposed entries MUST use the `0xFFXXXX` range, where `XXXX` corresponds to the proposed official identifier’s first four nibbles.

Temporary identifiers are:
- for development only
- not part of the official catalog
- not valid as final identifiers
- replaceable at any time
- subject to renaming by the maintainer before acceptance

## 5. Lifecycle model

Every `TECH_ID` and `NODE_IMP` follows the project lifecycle.

The lifecycle is:

- Proposed
- Experimental
- Active
- Legacy
- Retired

### Proposed
Proposed items are development-stage definitions not yet admitted to the official catalog. They use temporary identifiers in the `0xFFXXXX` range.

### Experimental
Experimental items are officially admitted to the catalog but MAY change or be removed without stability guarantees.

### Active
Active items are approved for deployment and intended for general use.

### Legacy
Legacy items SHOULD NOT be newly deployed; existing use MAY continue and SHOULD be supported by Active implementations.

### Retired
Retired items MUST NOT be newly deployed; existing instances SHOULD be decommissioned or updated.

Once an item exits Experimental status:
- its definition is frozen
- material changes require a new identifier
- the previous identifier remains immutable

If a spec modification renders an Active item non-compliant, the relevant item will be demoted to Legacy or Retired.

A material change includes, for example:
- behavior
- interfaces
- semantics
- hardware composition
- firmware build definition
- manufacturing definition
- packaging definition
- attribute bindings
- reproducibility fingerprint

## 6. Immutable items and bug fixes

Once a `TECH_ID` or `NODE_IMP` exits the Experimental lifecycle state, its technical definition is frozen.

Bug fixes, behavioral changes, implementation replacements, or compatibility corrections for frozen items MUST be implemented through allocation of a new identifier rather than through modification of the existing item.

GitHub Issues SHOULD be used to track:
- defects
- incompatibilities
- operational limitations
- proposed corrections
- replacement discussions

A correction workflow will typically:
1. open or reference an Issue;
2. introduce a new Proposed entry implementing the correction;
3. review and allocate an official identifier;
4. transition the previous identifier to Legacy or Retired if appropriate.

Lifecycle transitions do not modify the technical definition of an item.

## 7. What to submit

A contribution that introduces or changes a catalog entry should include:

- the proposed identifier or temporary identifier
- the human-readable name
- the descriptive rationale
- the relevant specification text
- the implementation artifacts, if applicable
- the hardware specification, if applicable
- the firmware build and reproducibility material, if applicable
- the known limitations and bugs

If the contribution proposes a new `NODE_IMP`, it should also identify:
- the associated `TECH_ID`s
- the hardware revision or manufacturing snapshot
- the firmware hash or build result
- the hardware specification fingerprint, when relevant

## 8. Submission workflow

Before opening a pull request:
1. create or update the relevant Proposed material
2. keep temporary identifiers local to the branch or draft
3. ensure the proposed bundle is internally coherent
4. ensure the proposed bundle does not conflict with existing official entries
5. prepare the descriptive text and implementation artifacts separately

During review, maintainers may:
- rename identifiers
- split or merge entries
- request more detail
- request reproducibility evidence
- request hardware clarification
- request catalog restructuring

Do not assume that a proposal will keep its temporary names or its original structure.

If a contribution bundles catalog items with proposed modifications to normative documents (specification text, allocation tables, lifecycle rules), the spec modifications MUST be submitted as a separate pull request. The catalog item pull request MUST reference the spec modification pull request and declare the dependency explicitly.

The maintainer may admit catalog items to Experimental status while the associated spec modification pull request remains open. The catalog items will not exit Experimental status until the associated spec modification is resolved.

## 9. Review criteria

A contribution is easier to accept when it is:
- clear
- internally consistent
- minimal
- reproducible
- aligned with existing catalog structure
- compatible with the Core Specification and Annex A
- explicit about dependencies and assumptions

A contribution may be rejected or revised if it:
- introduces unnecessary reinvention
- duplicates an existing solution without clear justification
- weakens determinism or auditability
- relies on hidden assumptions
- blurs the distinction between Proposed and official identifiers
- conflicts with the namespace or lifecycle rules

## 10. Experimental bundles

It is acceptable to develop a bundle of interacting `TECH_ID`s and `NODE_IMP`s as Proposed material before official allocation.

Such bundles should be treated as working drafts.

The maintainer may accept part of a bundle, split it, rename it, or replace temporary identifiers with official ones. Proposed work should therefore be written so that renaming is easy and does not break the structure of the proposal.

## 11. Forks

Forking is permitted.

A fork may:
- continue development
- modify the repository
- establish its own governance
- create its own identifier namespace

A fork that does so MUST adopt a different `MAGIC`.

A fork should not present itself as the canonical Codename Domodossola project unless it remains under the canonical maintainer governance and namespace.

## 12. Licensing boundaries

Different repository paths may use different licenses.

Contributors should read the license file in the relevant directory before submitting changes there.

If a contribution spans multiple license domains, it should be structured so that each part remains clearly attributable to the correct directory and license.

## 13. Deployment configuration examples

Real-world deployment configurations are private by default.

The `docs/examples/` directory exists for voluntarily contributed, anonymised examples. A contribution to this directory:

- MUST contain no real site-identifying information;
- MUST contain no real cryptographic material, keys, or UIDs;
- MUST contain no personal data;
- SHOULD represent a realistic deployment pattern useful to others;
- SHOULD be clearly marked with its anonymisation status.

The maintainer may decline an example submission if anonymisation appears incomplete or if the content does not add illustrative value beyond existing examples.

Deployment configurations used in production MUST NOT be submitted to this repository, even in modified form, unless they have been fully anonymised.

## 14. Practical contribution notes

Prefer small, reviewable pull requests.

When in doubt:
- propose the minimal change
- preserve existing identifiers
- keep descriptive text and implementation artifacts aligned
- make explicit whether a file is Proposed or frozen

## 15. Final note

The project values clarity, explicit boundaries, and reproducible structure.

If a contribution is technically useful but does not yet fit the official namespace, it may still be useful as Proposed material. The maintainer will decide whether it becomes part of the catalog, and under which official identifier.